Gapminder (Tableau Dashboard)

Jaime Pantoja

Introduction

This script is designed to clean a dataset from Gapminder, which will be published later on a Tableau dashboard. The first step involves obtaining the data from the Gapminder website. After that, the script joins and cleans the files to create a single dataset, making it easier to use in Tableau.

Get the data.

We get the data from gapminder.org and import it to the environment, reference on how to use read_csv funciton can be found here

gini <- read_csv("gini.csv")
density <- read_csv("population_density_per_square_km.csv")
population <- read_csv("population_total.csv")

Pivot tables

We have to pivot the tables in a long format. Reference on how to do it link

pivot_gini <- gini %>%
  pivot_longer(-country, names_to = "year", values_to = "gini_score")

pivot_density <- density %>%
  pivot_longer(-country, names_to = "year", values_to = "density")

pivot_population <- population %>%
  pivot_longer(-country, names_to = "year", values_to = "population")

Join the tables

We join the three tables based on the year and country and drop the rows with N/A observations. In addition, we convert the year into a numeric value so its easier to create an interactive dashboard in tableau.

data_set <- pivot_gini %>% 
  
  ## We join the data sets into one
  
  left_join(pivot_density,  by = c("year", "country")) %>% 
  left_join(pivot_population, by = c("year", "country")) %>%
  
  ## Omit the NA values
  
  na.omit() %>%
  
  ## Convert variables 'as numeric' format
  
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year),
         density = as.numeric(density)) %>% 
  
   
  
  ## ORGANIZE POPULATION VARIABLE
  
  # Create label variable 
  
  mutate(label = 
          case_when(stri_detect_fixed(population, "M") ~ "M",
                    stri_detect_fixed(population, "k")  ~ "K",
                    stri_detect_fixed(population, "B")  ~ "B",
                    TRUE  ~ "same")) %>% 
  
  # Take only the number from the string and convert it as numeric
  
  mutate( onlynumber = mgsub(population, c("M", "K","B","same"), c("", "", "", "")))     %>%
  mutate( onlynumber = as.numeric(onlynumber)) %>% 
  
  # Multiply the onlynumber column to get the population as a number 
  
  mutate(population_2 = case_when(label == "B" ~ onlynumber*1000000000,
                                  label == "M" ~ onlynumber*1000000,
                                  label == "K" ~ onlynumber*1000,
                                  TRUE ~ onlynumber)) %>% 
  
  # Select only the variables that will be used to create the dashboard.
  
  select(-(c( 5, 6, 7))) %>% 
  
  filter(year < 2022) 
  
data_set

Export (XLSX)

Now we save the data set as an xlsx file to later create the Tableau dashboard

write.xlsx(data_set, "dataset.xlsx")

Tableau Dashboard.

After the data is exported, we create the dashboard in Tableau the final result can be seeing in this link or down below.

As a reference Tableau dashboards can be imported using the embeded code of the dashboard. The code needs to be separated into the HTMl and JS. The JS portion needs to be included in a new code chunk of js and then the viz will be plot in the markdown file. In this video explains how to do this process.
